Jord <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dariathvaz>Dariath Vaz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 37<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(11/4/02 2:06:54 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3446.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wireless Internet</span><hr size=1> Most wireless internet connections would rely on a physical internet service of some sort connected to a wireless access point, which in turn the users of that access point need to have either a physical connection to it or a wireless ethernet card configured to communicate with the AP.<br>
<br>
So basically, if you have your wireless AP connected to a 56k, then you'll have wireless 56k.. connect it to cable and you'll have wireless cable internet.<br>
<br>
Though a search on Yahoo.com or Google.com would probably answer many more of your question much better than I can. (And wow, would be so much easier too!)<br>
<br>
As for &quot;possible&quot; wireless access... if the neighborhood he lives in or building or whatever has it and offers it then you get to split it with the rest of the residents.   If he plans on mooching it off some unsecured access point near him, then that's just lame.<br>
<br>
-Dariath <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=prybutok@vazaellecommunitycenter>Prybutok</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I Live Here</span><br>  Posts: 1125<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(11/4/02 2:30:43 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3446.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://prybutok.homestead.com/files/djprymini.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wireless Internet</span><hr size=1> Nope, its not lame, its what wi-fi is all about. People point their stations out towards parks and plazas, restaurants and coffeehouses.<br>
