[edit] - This is from my personal expericence in a neighborhood I used to live in.. Within range of my house, there were 12 unsecured points that I could access with no problem.  3 of those 12, I knew personally, and they had no clue that other people could access it outside their home. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dariathvaz>Dariath Vaz</A> at: 11/4/02 4:06:44 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=aurianne>Aurianne</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_fire.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Mana Whore</span><br>  Posts: 1379<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(11/4/02 9:33:01 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3446.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wireless Internet</span><hr size=1> Dunno about you, but AirCard is expensive around here. But that's a different technology entirely: that's essentially a cellular inet connection that works anywhere in the province. Well, anywhere there's digital cell coverage, but that's about 95% of inhabited areas in Ontario. You're billed based on how much you use, $100 CDN/100MB is the most economical rate from Bell, the only provider in Canada. You also have to buy the modem, which is ~$600.<br>
<br>
To put things in perspective, I'm paying $70 for static IP, 2.2MB/512k ADSL, 25GB/month transfer, commercial-level connection (99.5% guaranteed uptime, if they come below that I get a refund) with permission to run whatever server I want, and that includes the modem rental.<br>
<br>
There's also a radio internet provider, Look, but they're not taking new customers at the moment. They're also expensive, but broadband. (<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.look.ca)">www.look.ca)</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
<br>
Only reason to get Radio internet is if you don't have cable (as in, no cables actually going to the house, which is fairly common in the country), and you're too far away from the CO for DSL. 128k ISDN is cheaper than Radio, and it's more reliable.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Now... if he's talking about a wireless access point with a cable/xDSL connection, it's a whole different discussion. I'm using 802.11b for my home network, and the speed is 11mbit. Much faster than Cable/ADSL, and you won't notice a significant performance loss.<br>
<br>
A word of caution, though, be careful of topography when placing the wireless access point. If there's any concrete walls between your computer and the access point, the reception will go in the toilet. ATM, I have mine in the basement, and when I walk over the threshold between the original house and the sun room (added after the house was built, foundation wall between AP and sunroom) the reception goes from &quot;Excellent&quot; to &quot;Low&quot; and sometimes &quot;Very Low&quot;.<br>
<br>
The other thing you'll notice are nodes and antinodes. These are lines of poor reception (node) and excellent reception (antinode) that are caused by having two transmitter antennae very close to each other, and their radio waves cancelling each other out and stacking. You will see points in range of the AP where reception is &quot;Very Low&quot; or even no access available that are literally 5 feet away from an &quot;Excellent&quot; point.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Anyway.... if it's AirCard, don't get it. If it's Radio, *only* if there's no other options. If it's Cable/xDSL with a wireless Access Point, then get it.<br>
<br>
