<br>
The Channel is easy. There's 13 possibilities, less in some areas. The strength of encryption is easy. There's 2 possibilities for most network setups. The SSID, however, is not, assuming the person setting up the network is wise enough to disable the broadcast SSID, and not use something obvious. Certain OS's have trouble if you've disabled the Broadcast SSID, but it's easy enough to configure them manually so they don't have to broadcast, and easier still to just avoid those OS's.<br>
<br>
When you can't find out what the SSID for the network you're trying to crack is, and the network is using a non-standard channel (by default, channel 6. Also really easy to change), the wireless network might as well not be there, because you won't see it. It's not like you turn on a computer and see all of the available SSID's. You need to broadcast, which is answered by all of the base stations in range which tell you, using standard encryption/channels, what SSID and channel they're working on. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=cerosofvazaelle>Ceros of Vazaelle</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I Live Here</span><br>  Posts: 1026<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(11/6/02 12:43:11 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3446.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: .</span><hr size=1> I don't think that it's as hard to find networks without knowing their ssid's as you think.<br>
